715983f-a.title: Manhattan: Amsterdam Avenue - Cathedral Parkway - 113th St.
715983f-a.text:
Construction on New York's great cathedral to be resumed soon.

New photo of the Protestant Episcopal Cathedral of Saint John the Divine, on which construction is to be resumed soon. This photo shows the apse, or East end, with seven re_isting chapels; and the crossing, with its temporary dome.

The nave, or staff of the croon, which this completed church will form, is the next part to be built. It is also planned to erect a great tower, 500 feet high, above the present, temporary dome.
March 10, 1924  Underwood and Underwood

Even in its unfinished condition the Cathedral represents an expenditure of more than $5,000,000 and when completed will have cost four times as much. There will be seats for 7,000 persons. Some of the seven chapels are as commodious as many churches. It is expected that the Cathedral will be completed within ten years. - Review of Reviews

Neg #2601

715990f-a.title: Manhattan: Amsterdam Avenue - Cathedral Parkway - 113th Street
715990f-a.text:
OLD WORLD GRANDEUR IN NEW WORLD CATHEDRALS. CATHEDRAL OF SAINT JOHN THE DIVINE.

New York --- the ambulatory of the Cathedral. This is a passage about twenty feet wide which runs completely around the choir and gives access to the seven chapels of tongues. At the left of the photo shows the tomb of the founder of the Cathedral, Bishop Horatio Potter, sixth Bishop of New York. Its position, immediately behind the altar is that traditionally reserved for the founder of a cathedral. It was designed in the English Gothic style of the Fifteenth Century after studies of the tomb of Edward the Confessor, in Westminster Abbey. The photo was taken from the doorway of the Chapel of St. Martin of Tours. In the distance is the wrought iron screen before the Chapel of Saint Columba and beyond that the screen before the chapel of St. Boniface is invisible.
Dec. 2, 1924.
International Newsreel from the Review of Reviews.
